WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.440
Hi everyone, I'm super bummed I can't be there in person, but I'm really excited to be able

00:00:11.440 --> 00:00:20.240
to talk to you all today. My name is Fonty and I am a biologist. This here is my office.

00:00:20.240 --> 00:00:24.120
And for the past 10 years of my career, I've been trying to understand some of the complexities

00:00:24.120 --> 00:00:30.440
of our natural world. More recently, I came across an opportunity to work with other biologists

00:00:30.440 --> 00:00:35.840
to transform their ideas into R packages. And suddenly I found myself in this really

00:00:35.840 --> 00:00:41.240
unfamiliar landscape. There were all these new concepts I didn't understand, and I didn't

00:00:41.240 --> 00:00:47.520
know where to start. Up until this point of my career, I considered myself as an R code

00:00:47.520 --> 00:00:52.520
consumer. I used code developed by other package maintainers to get to the answers for my research

00:00:52.520 --> 00:00:59.840
questions. And the expectation now felt like I had to become an R code producer. And the

00:00:59.840 --> 00:01:04.279
difference between these two roles felt really intimidating. And I think this is a really

00:01:04.279 --> 00:01:10.040
common experience when you're trying to first pick up a new skill. So in spite of all these

00:01:10.040 --> 00:01:15.760
mixed feelings, I followed my instincts and used my skills as a biologist to navigate

00:01:15.760 --> 00:01:20.239
through this R package landscape. And today I want to share with you all my field guide

00:01:20.239 --> 00:01:26.040
to writing your first R package. So this field guide isn't a step-by-step walkthrough.

00:01:26.040 --> 00:01:30.400
If you want, you can check out my workshop that I wrote for R ladies. And it's not, this

00:01:30.400 --> 00:01:34.360
field guide isn't really about the technical stuff either. As you heard in Jenny slash

00:01:34.360 --> 00:01:39.559
Hadley's talk earlier on before, the R packages book is really an incredible resource for

00:01:39.559 --> 00:01:47.400
that. Instead, this field guide is an encouragement to start your first R package, a very gentle

00:01:47.400 --> 00:01:52.080
stroll through one, and some of my tips on how to deal with the things that you're likely

00:01:52.080 --> 00:01:59.800
to encounter along the way. My hope is to support and help those that feel really overwhelmed

00:01:59.800 --> 00:02:04.440
about this process, which was me at the beginning, and to also remind those seasoned package

00:02:04.440 --> 00:02:09.440
maintainers of what the beginner's mindset is like, and to encourage them to use some

00:02:09.440 --> 00:02:15.000
of the ideas I share today as a way to support those who are learning the ropes. So you might

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:19.800
be thinking, why go through all this effort in building an R package? But I hope from

00:02:19.800 --> 00:02:26.720
the content from all the other previous speakers, that the reason might be more apparent. But

00:02:26.720 --> 00:02:31.520
I'd like to also think about it like this. The code that you wrote for a particular project

00:02:31.520 --> 00:02:35.320
that's now hidden away in your directories may actually be a solution to another data

00:02:35.320 --> 00:02:40.880
scientist's problem. And maybe with some tweaks, it could be a solution to 10 more data scientists'

00:02:40.880 --> 00:02:47.039
problem. What I'm trying to say is that the impact of your code cannot be truly realized

00:02:47.039 --> 00:02:52.839
until it's in a shareable format. And that's where the R package comes in. So for us to

00:02:52.839 --> 00:02:57.039
go on this journey together, we're going to need a few things. And these packages have

00:02:57.039 --> 00:03:02.919
already been mentioned in these previous talks. So use this and dev tools are essential to

00:03:02.919 --> 00:03:08.839
the package building tool belt. And as Matt has alluded, it's great to store your package

00:03:08.839 --> 00:03:15.360
on GitHub so you can unlock things like using the GitHub issues and all the goodness that

00:03:15.360 --> 00:03:23.880
GitHub has to offer. So where would we begin? Whenever I enter a new landscape for a walk,

00:03:23.880 --> 00:03:29.960
I like to get my hands on a map. So here is a really rough sketch of a map of an R package.

00:03:29.960 --> 00:03:34.279
At its core, your R package contains your ideas, your functions or data that you want

00:03:34.279 --> 00:03:38.360
to share with the community. Next to those things are your documentation. These are your

00:03:38.360 --> 00:03:42.559
help files and vignettes to give your users some guidance on how to interact with your

00:03:42.559 --> 00:03:49.759
R package. There's also something to describe your R package. So this description file will

00:03:49.759 --> 00:03:55.080
give the user some higher level information about who wrote the R package, what it does

00:03:55.080 --> 00:04:01.880
generally, what dependencies it may have and where to go if they have any questions. There's

00:04:01.880 --> 00:04:06.479
something called a namespace. This controls what comes into your R package. So what functions

00:04:06.479 --> 00:04:11.119
you're borrowing from other packages and what goes out of your R package, what gets

00:04:11.119 --> 00:04:17.440
made available to your user when they load your R package into memory. Most packages

00:04:17.440 --> 00:04:23.040
will contain tests. These, I think, are the most elusive part of an R package. These ensure

00:04:23.040 --> 00:04:29.399
that your R package is behaving as it should and to let you know when it isn't. What I

00:04:29.399 --> 00:04:33.519
really like about having a map of an R package is that it breaks up what seems like a really

00:04:33.519 --> 00:04:39.160
complex idea into these smaller manageable pieces. And so as you're learning, you can

00:04:39.160 --> 00:04:43.640
focus on one thing at a time. And so also using this map, you can see the interconnections

00:04:43.640 --> 00:04:49.480
between all these subcomponents. And as Hadley had mentioned before, you don't have to put

00:04:49.480 --> 00:04:54.880
these components together using the function create package and use test that. These functions

00:04:54.880 --> 00:05:01.480
will lay down the foundation of the R package and this is where you're likely to begin.

00:05:01.480 --> 00:05:05.920
So as you're building your R package, questions will likely come up and this is totally not

00:05:05.920 --> 00:05:12.320
natural and normal. And when they do, I invite you to be curious. And one way you can do

00:05:12.320 --> 00:05:17.880
that is by using what I call the science poke. So the science poke originated from me going

00:05:17.880 --> 00:05:22.440
on nature walks and coming across something new and peculiar and me grabbing a stick and

00:05:22.440 --> 00:05:27.040
investigating it from a safe distance. So in your R package, science pokes are really

00:05:27.040 --> 00:05:32.320
simple ways to help you get unstuck and that are really low effort and low stakes. So for

00:05:32.320 --> 00:05:37.799
example, I was showing my friend Mark how to write his first R package and he goes,

00:05:37.799 --> 00:05:41.880
how do you add package documentation? And I'm like, well, what do you mean? He said,

00:05:41.880 --> 00:05:46.480
oh, it's that piece of writing that pops up when you call the help file for deep liar,

00:05:46.480 --> 00:05:52.019
for example. And I said, off the top of my head, I don't know, but there are functions

00:05:52.019 --> 00:05:57.339
in use this to add a read me, add vignettes and add articles. Maybe there's something

00:05:57.339 --> 00:06:02.660
in there for package documentation. And so Mark and I poked around the namespace for

00:06:02.660 --> 00:06:09.140
use this and found a relevant looking function for his purposes. The next thing we did was

00:06:09.140 --> 00:06:13.220
to call the help file for use package docs to figure out what it does and how to use

00:06:13.220 --> 00:06:20.540
it and if it's really suited for his purposes. And that was all it took to get Mark unstuck.

00:06:20.540 --> 00:06:25.380
Another way I like to get unstuck is actually to have a poke around in the GitHub repository

00:06:25.380 --> 00:06:30.100
of an existing R package. There's something super comforting in seeing another programmer's

00:06:30.100 --> 00:06:35.660
code doing exactly what you want to achieve. It's like holding the answers to an exam that

00:06:35.660 --> 00:06:40.299
you never got to prepare for. And it just gives you that much bit of confidence to take

00:06:40.299 --> 00:06:45.059
inspiration for their code and to try things out in your own R package. Which leads me

00:06:45.059 --> 00:06:50.339
to my next point is that experimenting with your code is a super effective way in getting

00:06:50.339 --> 00:06:57.140
unstuck. And the idea is that you change one thing at a time in your code and call the

00:06:57.140 --> 00:07:02.019
functions document, which updates your documentation, or load all, which loads a preview of the

00:07:02.019 --> 00:07:08.739
recent changes. And doing this, you can see the immediate effects of the changes you've

00:07:08.739 --> 00:07:13.820
made onto the R package. And it's through this iterative cycle that you can figure out

00:07:13.899 --> 00:07:22.299
how mechanics of an R package works. So, as your R package takes shape, you're going to

00:07:22.299 --> 00:07:26.380
come to a point where you're going to release it to the community. And that can feel a bit

00:07:26.380 --> 00:07:31.420
scary. So, I just want to say, whether it's a bug that you've uncovered post-release or

00:07:31.420 --> 00:07:37.540
someone's launched a GitHub issue or a feature request or a question, all of these unexpected

00:07:37.540 --> 00:07:41.940
encounters are really part of the package building process. And when it comes to that

00:07:41.940 --> 00:07:47.859
time, I invite you to embrace all that uncertainty and all its glory. And to treat those steps

00:07:47.859 --> 00:07:52.820
as an extension to building your R package and not your reflection of your ability as

00:07:52.820 --> 00:07:59.220
a package developer. As a matter of fact, whenever I go on field trips with my friends,

00:07:59.220 --> 00:08:07.059
and sometimes we're lucky enough to come across another creature in the nature, 100% of the

00:08:07.059 --> 00:08:12.899
time, all these unexpected encounters are considered as positive and enriching experiences.

00:08:12.899 --> 00:08:17.059
They teach me something about the diverse life forms across all these different landscapes.

00:08:17.059 --> 00:08:21.700
And I think the same can be said about the code bugs that we uncover in our R packages.

00:08:21.700 --> 00:08:26.019
They teach us something about the context that the bug has been produced. You'll learn how to

00:08:26.019 --> 00:08:32.659
detect them in your tests. And ultimately, addressing the bugs becomes in this iterative

00:08:32.659 --> 00:08:39.780
cycle that leads to the improvement of your R package. And in some cases, these bugs can

00:08:39.780 --> 00:08:46.179
actually be sources of inspiration for new features. But I understand that our initial

00:08:46.179 --> 00:08:51.859
reaction to bugs and anything uncertain is to resist. So if you want to feel more prepared

00:08:51.859 --> 00:08:57.700
for these things, I suggest you to seek out the bugs. So whenever I'm on field trips with my

00:08:57.700 --> 00:09:02.340
friends, we don't wait for some cool animal to cross our path. We go looking for them. So we'll

00:09:02.340 --> 00:09:08.020
be flipping rocks or turning over logs. And you can do the same with your R package. You can get

00:09:08.020 --> 00:09:12.739
your coding buddies to try it out and give you some feedback or get someone to read your

00:09:12.739 --> 00:09:21.700
documentation with a fresh pair of eyes. So I hope by seeing how I've approached writing R

00:09:21.780 --> 00:09:27.539
packages has demystified some of that process and dispelled that hesitation to start.

00:09:28.500 --> 00:09:32.900
If there's one take home from this talk, I hope that it's whether you're a seasoned package

00:09:32.900 --> 00:09:37.700
maintainer or just starting out with your first R package, is that I hope we can all code more

00:09:37.700 --> 00:09:42.900
like a biologist. By that, I mean be more curious and be more willing to scientifically poke and

00:09:42.900 --> 00:09:48.179
prod at your code to get it to work and to overall be more embracing about all the things that you're

00:09:48.179 --> 00:09:53.940
going to encounter along the way. Because we as an R community are going to need all the ideas we

00:09:53.940 --> 00:09:59.859
can get to sustain this thriving, growing R ecosystem. And with that, I know this is a

00:09:59.859 --> 00:10:05.700
short talk. I want to thank you all for listening and tuning in. And I'm, yeah, thank you, Posit,

00:10:05.700 --> 00:10:10.979
for inviting me. I'm happy to hear feedback or questions. Thank you.

00:10:18.739 --> 00:10:23.700
Thank you, Fanti. That was great. I do have one quick question. I was wondering if you had any

00:10:23.700 --> 00:10:29.460
advice on, like, marketing that first R package to either your friends or people on the internet

00:10:29.460 --> 00:10:37.299
after you've built it. Oh, I generally, because if you're building an R package, it's generally

00:10:37.299 --> 00:10:44.099
for a dedicated community. I think it's initially before the mass release, I would maybe shoulder

00:10:44.099 --> 00:10:51.780
tap or message a few folks that would find that R package interesting as a kind of soft release.

00:10:52.340 --> 00:10:56.659
After that, I would suggest relying on social media. Like,

00:10:56.659 --> 00:11:00.900
Mastodon is a really great thing for reaching out to the R community.

00:11:02.900 --> 00:11:04.979
Thanks. Are there any questions from the audience?

00:11:11.940 --> 00:11:15.859
No? Okay. Thank you, Fanti. We really appreciate you coming in.

00:11:15.859 --> 00:11:25.140
No worries. Thank you.

